SCRUM — IBM'S PRIMARY DELIVERY FRAMEWORK
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Scrum is IBM's most-used Agile framework for Garage delivery. It relies on
fixed-length iterative sprints, typically 1-4 weeks.

SCRUM TEAM ROLES:
- PRODUCT OWNER: Owns the product backlog. Prioritizes work based on business
  value. Uses Funnel approach to gather requirements; uses Firewall to protect
  the team during sprints.
- SCRUM MASTER: Coach, not leader. Keeps the team adhering to Agile practices.
  Removes impediments. Facilitates ceremonies.
- DEVELOPMENT TEAM: Self-organizing, cross-functional team of 3-9 members.
  Includes developers, designers, QA, and other SMEs.

SCRUM CEREMONIES (also called Agile ceremonies):

1. SPRINT PLANNING
   When: Beginning of each sprint
   Who: Full scrum team
   Duration: Typically 2-4 hours for a 2-week sprint
   Purpose: Team decides which product backlog items to tackle and HOW they
   will deliver them. The team commits to a Sprint Goal.
   IBM practice: PM presents prioritized backlog. Team estimates and selects
   stories that fit within the sprint capacity.

2. DAILY STANDUP (Daily Scrum)
   When: Every day of the sprint
   Who: Development team (Scrum Master facilitates)
   Duration: Maximum 15 minutes — strictly timebox
   Format: Each team member answers 3 questions:
   - What did I complete yesterday?
   - What will I complete today?
   - What is blocking me?
   IBM practice: Keep this focused. Blockers are raised here; solutions are
   discussed AFTER the standup with only the relevant people.

3. SPRINT REVIEW (Sprint Demo)
   When: End of each sprint
   Who: Full team + stakeholders + Sponsor Users
   Duration: 1-2 hours for a 2-week sprint
   Purpose: Team demonstrates DONE work to stakeholders. Stakeholders provide
   feedback. IBM's Funnel/Firewall PM practice: this is the feedback loop.
   IBM practice: Only DONE (potentially shippable) work is demonstrated.
   Incomplete work is not shown. This maintains trust with the client.

4. SPRINT RETROSPECTIVE
   When: After Sprint Review, before next Sprint Planning
   Who: Scrum team (no external stakeholders)
   Duration: 1-2 hours
   Purpose: Team reflects on HOW they worked, not WHAT they built.
   Three questions: What went well? What could improve? What will we commit
   to doing differently next sprint?
   IBM practice: Blameless retrospectives. Focus on systems and processes,
   not individuals.

5. BACKLOG REFINEMENT (Grooming)
   When: Mid-sprint, typically once per sprint
   Who: Product Owner + Development Team
   Duration: 1-2 hours
   Purpose: Review, estimate, and clarify upcoming backlog items so Sprint
   Planning runs smoothly.

