IBM AGILE SQUAD STRUCTURE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

IBM Garage operates through squads — small, cross-functional, self-organizing
teams typically of 5-9 people.

IBM Squad structure for a typical consulting engagement:
- Squad Leader / Scrum Master (IBM consultant, EDT-certified)
- Product Owner (IBM consultant, sometimes client-side co-PO)
- Architect (IBM consultant)
- Developers (2-4, mix of IBM and client)
- QA / Test (1-2)
- Designer / UX (1, often shared across squads)
- Client SME (1-2, embedded from client side)

WORK STREAMS in IBM squads:
IBM Agile squads work on two consecutive work streams simultaneously:
1. CLIENT OPERATIONS STREAM: Delivering the sprint's committed work
2. PROCESS IMPROVEMENT STREAM: Analyzing how to do the client work better

Squad members explore potential improvements, create an execution strategy,
and deliver it in a two-week sprint. Process improvement is continuous, not
just at retrospectives.

THE T-SHAPED SKILLS MODEL:
Each squad member has:
- DEPTH: Deep expertise in their primary area (developer, QA, designer, etc.)
- BREADTH: Enough breadth to help teammates and understand the whole system

IBM does not silo people by role — a developer can help with testing, a QA
can help with documentation, etc. This prevents bottlenecks.

