BACKLOG MANAGEMENT — IBM PRACTICES
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

BACKLOG HIERARCHY (from strategic to tactical):
- THEMES: Broad strategic focus areas aligned to business objectives
- EPICS: Large bodies of work, broken down into stories. Not completable in
  a single sprint.
- FEATURES: Specific functions that deliver value to users.
- USER STORIES: "As a [user], I want to [action] so that [outcome]"
  Format ensures the team understands WHO benefits and WHY.
- TASKS: Technical subtasks within a user story (hours, not days)
- BUGS / DEFECTS: Issues found in testing or production

IBM PM FUNNEL AND FIREWALL PRACTICE:
- FUNNEL: PM runs stakeholder workshops to gather requirements. Inputs:
  KPIs, Unique Selling Points (USPs), value propositions, high-level estimates,
  timelines. Output: prioritized backlog of features.
  Then: backlog refinement discussions with the development team to slice epics
  into actionable stories.
- FIREWALL: PM shields the team during sprints. No new requirements mid-sprint.
  All requests go through the PM's backlog process. This ensures the team
  achieves sprint goals and maintains predictable velocity.

OUTCOME-BASED ROADMAPS (OBRs):
IBM product managers use OBRs to connect product vision and business objectives
with high-level features. OBRs prevent teams from losing sight of overall
objectives when working through detailed sprint tasks.

