CONSULTANT QUICK REFERENCE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Q: Client team is unfamiliar with Agile. How do we onboard them quickly?
A: IBM recommends a "Garage experience" kickoff: run the first sprint as a
learning sprint. Lower velocity expectations. Invest time in ceremonies.
Pair IBM consultants with client counterparts (pair programming model applied
to ALL roles, not just developers).

Q: Sprint velocity is dropping week over week. What's happening?
A: Check five things: (1) Are there unresolved blockers from standups?
(2) Is scope being added mid-sprint? (3) Is the team attending too many
external meetings? (4) Are stories properly estimated and sized? (5) Is there
technical debt accumulation slowing new work?

Q: How do we handle a client who wants detailed status reports but Agile
doesn't produce traditional reports?
A: Use the Sprint Review demo as the status report. Stakeholders see working
software, not slide decks. Supplement with a one-page sprint summary: sprint
goal, stories completed, velocity, key decisions, blockers, next sprint goal.
This satisfies governance without creating documentation overhead.

Q: What's the right sprint length for a client engagement?
A: IBM defaults to 2-week sprints for most engagements. 1-week sprints when
velocity and feedback loops need to be very fast (early discovery phases).
3-4 week sprints only when the domain requires more protracted work cycles
(e.g., hardware integration, regulated environments with long testing cycles).
